## When to narrate during work

| Moment | What to say |
|--------|-------------|
| Starting research / exploration | `"Researching [topic]."` |
| Found something important | `"Found it. [one-line summary]."` |
| About to edit a file | `"Updating [filename]."` |
| Running a command / install | `"Running [command]."` |
| Waiting on a slow process | `"Still running. Hang tight."` |
| Spawning a subagent | `"Launching parallel agent for [task]."` |
| **Task complete** | **⚠️ Mandatory verbose spoken summary — see above** |

Mid-task narration (research, file edits, running commands) can stay short — one sentence is fine. Only the **completion summary** needs to be verbose.

---

## Parallel subagents

When using the Task tool to launch subagents, narrate before and after each launch:

```
speak → "Spinning up two agents in parallel."
→ launch Task A + Task B
speak → "Both agents running. Reporting back when done."
... finish ...
speak → "All done. [verbose summary]."
```

**Subagent voice (mandatory in subagent prompts):** each Task subagent must use the teen / young-adult pool only. Tell the subagent to run pick and speak with:

`$env:FRIDAY_TTS_SESSION='subagent'` and `pick-session-voice.py --subagent` before any `friday-speak.py`, and the same env on every `friday-speak.py` call. Main Cursor chat uses `FRIDAY_TTS_VOICE` from the environment (Jarvis by default); subagents stay on the separate sticky teen pool.

---

## Tone

- The user can speak casually; narration should be listenable, not a roleplay duel.
- Prefer clear, composed delivery — British-ish polish is fine but not mandatory on every line.
- Skip "I am an AI" filler; otherwise stay practical, not theatrical.
- Plays through whatever is set as the default Windows audio device
